metadata.name: Murals #221
metadata.description:
'Murals' is a collection of 256 abstract compositions born out of an intense period diving deeply into street art, pointillism and the inner workings of neural networks.

The work explores projection, refraction and abstraction of points as they ripple through multi-dimensional space-time. Points refract through multi-dimensional space to become shapes, which then become coordinate systems for the projections of new points that create a sense of form, texture, lighting, and material properties. 

The work is also a celebration of imperfections and how a combination of many tiny â€“ almost individually imperceptibly small â€“ imperfect details can shape our perceptions of form, materiality, mood. This is explored within this work through subtle uses of sprays, flecks, scuffs, cuts, grain, targets (projections of projections), construction lines, base projections, occasional glitches that cause curvature, bounced light, shadows, and more.

Features:

15 colour palettes: 
Scream, Night Bus, Double Backflip, Jaws, Sunday, Atom, Space, Tipex, 
Graphite, Leaf, Earth, Bubble Gum, Citrus, Jellyfish, Damp Concrete.

4 times of day (that create subtle changes in light colour):
Daylight, Winter Morning, Midnight, Sunset

2 Border types: 
Normal, Thin

Various features that subtly impact appearance surface textures and shard forms:
Metallic, Engrave, Number of Shards, Scuff Marks, Symmetry. 

Controls:
- Press [ S ] to save the work at its current image size as a PNG.
- Press [ 1 ] to set the image size to 1440 x 1944 pixels (default size)
- Press [ 2 ] to set the image size to 2880 x 3888 pixels
- Press [ 3 ] to set the image size to 4320 x 5832 pixels

- Press [ F ] to toggle freeform mode to create custom image sizes and aspect ratios
- Press [ R ] to reload the image (for use in freeform mode)

This work has been tested on Chrome and Safari on Mac OS, and also using an Android smartphone. Please make sure that it works on your device before minting. Based on testing (in May 2022), each work should take about 5-10 seconds to fully load on a laptop or desktop machine, and 15-20 seconds on a mobile device. The loading process is animated so you can watch the construction the static artwork during this time. 

This artwork is created with p5.js 

@nbswwit, 2022

metadata.name: Tenderness #16
metadata.description:
The lace aesthetic began to stir the minds of the public in the middle of the 20th century. With the light hand of Coco Chanel, the sexual revolution began to gain new traction, the consequence of which was the fashion designers' traditional idea of the beauty of the female female .

The images of the time absoluted the sexuality of the women. Every pattern, every curve and every hue was seen as something perfect, intriguing and hypnotic. The final touch of the "revolution" was the use of knitwear, which allowed the underwear to become even tighter and more provocative.

The idealized image of women in the dreams of men at that time was a vivid symbiosis of personality with elegant, feminine harmony, which embraces inspired the strongest individuals to create and to innovate.

Polina Arz Â© 

A professional Fashion designer and fashion artist whose work reflects the spirit of modernity and the world around us in the language of current trends and contemporary art.

metadata.name: Syzers #155
metadata.description:
Syzers is a generative synthesizer project with sounds altered by Tone JS.

Â·Â·Â·Â· On Tuesday, May 17, unsold editions will be burned Â·Â·Â·Â·

Visually it consists of 16 layers, in which more than 350 elements are combined randomly, generating synthesizers with unique environments and landscapes.
As for the sound, 40 tracks were recorded with analog synthesizers that were then assigned to each of the modules. These, combined in groups of 4, provide thousands of possible combinations. 
In addition, these sounds will be further modified by code effects that will randomly vary their properties.

Click to listen to the sounds

Many thanks to @Jpupper and @Fipiaggio for help with programming the sound part and @Purespider for the template. 
"FXHASH PFP Token Generator" https://github.com/PureSpider/fxhash-pfp

for best resolution "open live" then use the "download image" button on the lower right corner ;)

metadata.name: Inertia #192
metadata.description:
This project will be reserved and free for 48 hours, for all the holders of any of my projects!

The amount of reserves for each user will be equal to the amount of all the token held at 13:00 CEST [UTC+2] (May 23)
(example: user holds 3 "Figment" and 2 "ACCUMULATOR", will be able to mint "Inertia" 5 times)

48h from now I will update the reserves list and burn the remaining tokens

WARINING: The reserves will expire 48h after the drop! And a price for the unlocked mintables will be set (unreserved mints will not be free).

---

"Inertia is a property of matter by which it continues in its existing state of rest or uniform motion in a straight line, unless that state is changed by an external force."

Particles are blasted from 2 to 4 sides of the canvas, each particle has its own mass and it has to traverse a friction-field, once it loses its momentum completely it stops and leaves a trace, adding or subtracting light from the canvas.

The friction-field has 18 possible mutation kinds.
Mutations are high-friction zones of various shapes.

Made just with JS on a canvas
right-click to save

metadata.name: brushstroke #17
metadata.description:
Brushstroke is an algorithm to form a minimal, modern, artistic paint on a canvas. It mimics a painter's hand gesture to apply different types of strokes. Those strokes may vary from thin straight lines to fat curvy arcs. The direction of the strokes may change for each stroke or not. There may be an excessive amount of them as there may be just several. Strokes may intersect and form a group. It generates color palettes as an artist does. There are more than twenty parameters that give variety to pieces. 

Brushstroke is built on the p5.js library. As a way of saying thanks, you will contribute to the Processing Foundation by collecting this work.
